If we start with a generic quadratic equation and use completing the square to solve it, we can derive the quadratic formula:

  • If \(ax^2+bx+c=0\), then \[x~=~\frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]

Use the quadratic formula to find both solutions (rounded to the nearest hundredth) to the equation below.

\[9x^2+8x-2~=~0\]

  • \(x=\)
  • or
  • \(x=\)

Identify the parameters.

  • The quadratic coefficient: \(a=9\)
  • The linear coefficient: \(b=8\)
  • The constant: \(c=-2\)

Plug the numbers into the quadratic formula.

\[x~=~\frac{-(8)\pm \sqrt{(8)^2-4(9)(-2)}}{2(9)}\]

Simplify.

\[x~=~\frac{-8\pm \sqrt{64 +72}}{18}\]

Simplify MORE.

\[x~=~\frac{-8\pm \sqrt{136}}{18}\]

Now, plug both expressions into a calculator.

\[x~=~\frac{-8- \sqrt{136}}{18}~=~-1.092328 ~\approx -1.09\]

OR

\[x~=~\frac{-8+ \sqrt{136}}{18}~=~0.2034391 ~\approx 0.2\]

If you are using a basic (one-line) scientific calculator, you can type the expressions like:

(-8-sqrt(136))/(18)

(-8+sqrt(136))/(18)

Or maybe...

(-8-(136))/(18)

(-8+(136))/(18)

A rectangle's height is 2 meters longer than its width. The area is 40 square meters. In meters, what is the height? (Answers should be accurate within \(\pm 0.1\) meters)

Let \(x\) represent the height. The width is \(x-{2}\). The area of a rectangle equals the product of height times width.

\[40~=~x\cdot (x-{2})\]

Distribute the multiplication of \(x\) to the terms in parentheses.

\[40~=~x^{2}-{2}x\]

Subtract 40 from both sides.

\[0~=~x^{2}-{2}x-{40}\]

Now the right side of the equation is in standard form. We can identify \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) in order to use the quadratic formula.

\[a=1\] \[b=-2\] \[c=-40\]

Remember the formula.

\[x~=~\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]

Plug in the coefficients.

\[x~=~\frac{-(-2)\pm \sqrt{(-2)^2-4(1)(-40)}}{2(1)}\]

Simplify.

\[x~=~\frac{2\pm \sqrt{{4}+{160}}}{2}\]

Simplify more.

\[x~=~\frac{2\pm \sqrt{164}}{2}\]

Simplify more.

\[x~=~\frac{2\pm 2\sqrt{41}}{2}\]

Simplify more.\[x~=~1\pm \sqrt{41}\]

This (or, honestly, one of the earlier, less simplified expressions) can be put into a calculator to get the two possible values for \(x\) as decimal approximations. We are only interested in the positive solution.

\[f(x)~=~-6x^2-5x+7\]

Below, I've graphed \(y=f(x)\), and I've included the axis of symmetry as a dashed purple line and the vertex as a filled red dot.


Using the geometric significance of the quadratic formula, calculate \(h\), the horizontal coordinate of the vertex. The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).

Look at the quadratic formula, which tells us if our quadratic function is in standard form, like \(y=ax^2+bx+c\), then:

\[\text{roots of quadratic function} ~=~ \frac{-b}{2a}\pm\frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]

We were given a quadratic function in standard form. Identify the parameters.

  • The quadratic coefficient: \(a=-6\)
  • The linear coefficient: \(b=-5\)
  • The constant: \(c=7\)

The the geometric significance of the quadratic formula tells us that \(h=\frac{-b}{2a}\) and the distance of the roots to the axis of symmetry is \(\frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\). Use the formula to calculate \(h\).

\[\begin{align} h &= \frac{-b}{2a} \\\\ &= \frac{-(-5)}{2(-6)} \\\\ &= -0.4166667 \end{align}\]

  • The axis of symmetry is line \(x=-0.4166667\).
  • The vertex is point \((-0.4166667,\,8.0416667)\)
